    <h1 class="article-title">The Silver Mirror Reaction: Chemistry's Most Beautiful Test</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Discover how the Tollens test creates stunning silver mirrors while helping chemists identify aldehydes through elegant redox chemistry.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">R-CHO + 2Ag(NH₃)₂⁺ + 3OH⁻</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">R-COO⁻ + 2Ag + 4NH₃ + 2H₂O</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The silver mirror reaction, also known as the Tollens test, is one of the most visually stunning reactions in chemistry. When performed correctly, this test transforms the inside of a test tube into a brilliant silver mirror while simultaneously identifying the presence of aldehydes in a sample. Named after German chemist Bernhard Tollens, this reaction has been a staple in organic chemistry laboratories for over a century.</p>
  <p class="body-text">The reaction begins with Tollens' reagent, a solution containing silver ions complexed with ammonia, creating the diammine silver ion [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺. When this reagent encounters an aldehyde under basic conditions, a fascinating redox reaction occurs. The aldehyde acts as a reducing agent, donating electrons to the silver ions and causing them to be reduced to metallic silver, which deposits as a thin, reflective layer on the glass surface.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Why Does This Work?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">The silver mirror forms because aldehydes are easily oxidized compounds. They readily give up electrons to the silver ions in Tollens' reagent. As the silver ions gain electrons, they become neutral silver atoms that stick to the glass, creating the characteristic mirror finish. This is a classic example of a redox reaction where oxidation and reduction happen simultaneously.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">What makes this reaction particularly useful is its selectivity. While aldehydes readily react with Tollens' reagent to produce the silver mirror, ketones do not react under these conditions. This makes the test an excellent way to distinguish between these two types of carbonyl compounds. The reaction is so sensitive that even small amounts of aldehydes can be detected, making it valuable for both qualitative analysis and as a dramatic demonstration of redox chemistry principles.</p>

